{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff (request builder -> API client), not model judgment. A unit test of a helper could miss wiring/serialization bugs in the actual dispatched payload (MOCK-MISS). No real OS/network behavior is required (REAL-INFRA: no), and correctness does not depend on model output content (LLM-DEP: no). Rejected higher levels: System/Agentic are disqualified because behavior only checks request payload composition before/at dispatch, not live infra or model decisions.","test_description":"Wire classifier with an in-process fake API client that captures outbound requests. Invoke classify() with a taxonomy and assert the captured request contains the full label set (no omissions/reordering loss if order is specified).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure typically appears at boundary between response parsing/normalization and module return value, so test should exercise wired modules together (MOCK-MISS). No real infrastructure needed (REAL-INFRA: no). No dependence on model quality/content beyond injecting an invalid label string (LLM-DEP: no). Rejected higher levels: Agentic/System disqualified because a deterministic stubbed response is sufficient to trigger the failure mode.","test_description":"Use an in-process fake API returning an out-of-taxonomy label. Call classify(); assert returned value is exactly \"unknown\" and raw invalid label is not propagated.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is pure normalization determinism for identical input; single function/object boundary with no required I/O (MOCK-MISS indicates no module interaction required). REAL-INFRA: no, LLM-DEP: no, MULTI-STEP: no. Rejected higher levels: Integration/System/Agentic are disqualified because behavior text scopes to normalization step given identical raw responses.","test_description":"Call normalization function repeatedly with the same raw response fixture and taxonomy; assert identical output label every run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live API calls and consistency of model/provider decisions. A mock would hide real non-determinism and provider behavior drift (MOCK-HIDE, LLM-DEP: yes). Not Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification checks, not a chained multi-step agent pipeline. Rejected lower level Integration: disqualified by \"live API calls\" and dependence on real model outputs.","test_description":"Run N real classification calls for identical input against the provider; record returned labels and provider response payloads. Assert label stability when provider response is materially unchanged; flag inconsistency otherwise.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at interaction of token counting/policy enforcement with dispatch gating (module boundary), so Integration is the minimum reliable boundary (MOCK-MISS). No real OS/network is required (REAL-INFRA: no). Correctness does not depend on model output quality (LLM-DEP: no) because check is pre-dispatch. Rejected higher levels: System/Agentic disqualified by behavior text \"before dispatch.\"","test_description":"Configure a small budget and use fixtures above/below threshold with an in-process fake API client. Assert policy action (truncate or reject) occurs before send, and rejected requests are not dispatched.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.33,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This depends on real provider token accounting from an actual AI API invocation; stubbing usage can mask real mismatches between local estimates and provider-reported usage (MOCK-HIDE, LLM-DEP default applies because execution path requires real AI API). System was considered, but behavior is disqualified from staying at System because correctness hinges on provider model/tokenizer behavior, not just transport/OS effects.","test_description":"Execute real calls for representative documents and capture provider-reported usage fields. Assert observed total tokens do not exceed configured budget for the tested profile/model/prompt template.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the